      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tastemakers First</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Shaun Breidbart letter expresses horror at Frank Prial's July 19 Wine Talk column, which revealed that wine reviewers eliminated many wines by smell without ever tasting them (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I was horrified to read in Frank Prial's Wine Talk column (''For Inexpensive Upstarts, a Day of Glory,'' July 19) that wine reviewers eliminate many wines by smell without ever tasting them.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I was horrified to read in Frank Prial's Wine Talk column (''For Inexpensive Upstarts, a Day of Glory,'' July 19) that wine reviewers eliminate many wines by smell without ever tasting them.</p>
        <p>After all, people buy wine to drink, not to smell.</p>
        <p>At a chocolate-tasting seminar I conducted several years ago, most of the participants were enamored of  one particular brand of well-regarded European chocolate, until one person said, ''Yuck! It smells like Cheez Whiz!''</p>
        <p>She was right. It smelled awful.</p>
        <p>But it tasted just fine.</p>
        <p>And we were all interested in taste, not smell.</p>
        <p>SHAUN BREIDBART  Pelham, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
